I guess that a cellphone would use data (WiFi/4G/5G) when using GPS with a map application, the reason being is that the phone is comunicating with the network provider to download the map required to show your location.
Older GPS devices without dynamically updating maps (the maps are either burnt into ROM or on some sort of memory card, so they can be manually updated) shouldn't broadcast anything, because the device only receives broadcasts from the constealtion of GPS satellites orbiting the Earth, calculates position from that and then displays its location.

Hmmm... I think you are quite incorrect about the operation of GPS.  GPS positioning does not require sending any data at all.  It is a receive and process operation that compares signals a device receives from satellites.  The assumption is a tracker is sending this data via some other method (rf).  Your phone will do that for pretty much anything so it would essentially be useless for that (can determine the phone's radio is in operation).  You could also record tracking data without ever sending it anywhere.  I think the premise that "gps tracking" can be detected at all is fundamentally flawed.
